  (Shall gnats impede the bull?)</ref><note xml:id="ref_21136">THEY BRUSHED THE FOE...IMPEDE THE BULL [Allusion—historical—military] Sherman’s troops were in greater numbers and better supply than Confederate forces that attempted to rout the Federals on the march. Even the substantive Confederate force, Joseph Wheeler’s cavalry, hardly posed a threat to Sherman’s men. One small Confederate militia under the command of Brig. General Pleasant J. Phillips engaged Sherman’s rear guard near Griswoldville, GA on November 22. The Confederates were decimated in the skirmish; Union soldiers discovered afterward that Phillips’s troops were primarily young boys and elderly men (“Scorched Earth,” www.civilwar.org).
(Leslie McAbee)</note>
note xml:id="ref_21155">FOR BEHIND...MANIACS RAN [Allusion—military] William T. Sherman’s Special Field Orders, No. 120, indicates: “In districts and neighborhoods where the army is unmolested, no destruction of such property should be permitted; but should guerrillas or bushwhackers molest our march, or should the inhabitants burn bridges, obstruct roads, or other-wise manifest local hostility, then army commanders should order and enforce a devastation more or less relentless, according to the measure of such hostility” (The War of the Rebellion, 713).
(Leslie McAbee)</note>



<ref target="#ref_21135">The foragers</ref><note xml:id="ref_21135">THE FORAGERS [Allusion—military] In his Special Field Orders, No. 120, Sherman determined “[t]he army will forage liberally on the country during the march” (The War of the Rebellion: A Compilation of the Official Records of the Union and Confederate Armies, Series 1-Vol 39, 713). A selection of soldiers were organized as foragers to search out food and goods from plantations, modest homesteads, and slave cabins alike. These foragers earned the name “bummers” (“Scorched Earth,” www.civilwar.org).
Leslie McAbee</note>
